# Deeplink Vulnerability Findings â€” SmartReminder (com.samsung.android.app.reminder)

---

## [V-001] DetailActivity â€” Permission-Bypass via Intent Redirection to AddActivity (Confused Deputy)

**File:** `sources/com/samsung/android/app/reminder/ui/detail/view/DetailActivity.java`
**Severity:** High
**Class of flaw:** CWE-441 / CWE-926 â€” Unsafe Intent redirection and permission re-delegation.

### Summary
`DetailActivity` is `android:exported="true"` with **no** `android:permission` in the manifest and is reachable from any app (and partially from a web browser) via the following intent-filters:

| Filter | Scheme | Host | Category |
|--------|--------|------|----------|
| 1 | `uuid` | `reminder.uuid` | DEFAULT |
| 2 | `reminder` | `viewdetail` | DEFAULT (action `ReminderDetailView`) |
| 3 | `content` | `@string/string_detail_view_host_name` | DEFAULT |

In `onCreate(Bundle)` the activity:

1. Reads `uuid` from either the `getStringExtra("uuid")`, URI last path segment, or `?uuid=` query parameter (lines 43â€“68).
2. **Reuses the original, attacker-controlled Intent**: `Intent intent = getIntent();`
3. **Rewrites the target class**: `intent.setClass(getApplicationContext(), AddActivity.class);` (line 74).
4. Copies extras (`add_view_type`, `uuid`, `viewDetailFromCalendar`, `viewDetailFromNowBrief`, `viewDetailFromCalendarSearch`).
5. Forwards the reborn Intent to `AddActivity` via `y0.k(this, intent)` or `getApplicationContext().startActivity(getIntent())` (lines 102â€“107).

`AddActivity` is declared in AndroidManifest.xml as:
```xml
<activity
    android:name="com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.add.AddActivity"
    android:permission="com.samsung.android.app.reminder.permission.action.REGISTER"
    android:exported="true" ...>
```
i.e. it is **permission-protected**. But because the reminder app itself holds that permission, routing the Intent through `DetailActivity` (running in the reminder app's process) transparently **bypasses the permission check**.

### Why this is exploitable
* `DetailActivity` does **not** sanitise / validate any extras that were present on the incoming Intent â€” they are preserved across the `setClass()` call and delivered verbatim to `AddActivity`.
* `DetailActivity` does **not** call `intent.setComponent(null)` / `new Intent()`; it literally mutates and re-fires the attacker's Intent object.
* `startActivity(getIntent())` happens from the application context, so any caller-added flags (e.g. `FLAG_ACTIVITY_CLEAR_TASK`, `FLAG_GRANT_READ_URI_PERMISSION`, `FLAG_GRANT_WRITE_URI_PERMISSION`) are preserved.

### Attacker model
Any locally installed, **unprivileged** 3rd-party app (or, for filter 3, a colluding app that serves a `content://` URI) can:
* Silently launch `AddActivity` without holding `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.permission.action.REGISTER`.
* Pre-populate `AddActivity`'s extras (`add_view_type`, `uuid`, â€¦) to force:
  * **Edit mode against a specific victim reminder** â€” by supplying a known / brute-forced UUID (UUIDs of reminders are leaked through the Search provider and shared intent exports).
  * **Creation of phishing reminders** (e.g. fake "password reset" reminders with attacker-controlled text/time) that the user will later see in their own Reminder UI and may act on.
* Because `FLAG_GRANT_READ/WRITE_URI_PERMISSION` is preserved across the redirect, an attacker can grant the reminder app temporary read access to attacker-owned `content://` URIs that `AddActivity` may later resolve (image attachments, etc.) â€” useful for second-stage XXE / SSRF / path-traversal in the add pipeline.

### Proof-of-Concept (Kotlin, attacker app)
```kotlin
// Launched from any unprivileged 3rd-party application.
val victimUuid = "11111111-2222-3333-4444-555555555555" // any known/guessed UUID
val exploit = Intent(Intent.ACTION_VIEW).apply {
    // Route through the exported DetailActivity â€¦
    setClassName(
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder",
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.view.DetailActivity"
    )
    // â€¦ using any of the accepted deeplink URIs:
    data = Uri.parse("uuid://reminder.uuid/$victimUuid")
    // These extras are forwarded verbatim into AddActivity:
    putExtra("uuid", victimUuid)
    putExtra("add_view_type", 2)                 // 2 = EDIT
    putExtra("viewDetailFromCalendar", true)     // take alternate branch in y0.a()
    putExtra("is_from_calendar_search", true)
    addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK or
             Intent.FLAG_GRANT_READ_URI_PERMISSION or
             Intent.FLAG_GRANT_WRITE_URI_PERMISSION)
}
startActivity(exploit)
```
Equivalent one-liner via `adb` for testing:
```
adb shell am start -a android.intent.action.VIEW \
    -d "uuid://reminder.uuid/11111111-2222-3333-4444-555555555555" \
    -n com.samsung.android.app.reminder/com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.view.DetailActivity \
    --ei add_view_type 2 --es uuid 11111111-2222-3333-4444-555555555555
```
The victim observes `AddActivity` (edit view) opened against their own reminder data, even though the caller never held the protective permission.

### Root-cause fix recommendations
1. Construct a **fresh** `Intent` for the forwarded call instead of mutating `getIntent()`; copy only the whitelist of extras the downstream activity expects.
2. Call `intent.setComponent(new ComponentName(pkg, AddActivity))` only *after* stripping URI permission grant flags and `FLAG_ACTIVITY_*` flags that shouldn't leak.
3. Either give `DetailActivity` the same `android:permission=".action.REGISTER"` (so callers must hold it) **or** validate the incoming UUID belongs to a reminder owned by the calling package (the repository knows this).

