## [V-007] y0.a / PopOverUtils â€” `Intent.toUri(1)` Smuggling via `popover_intent` Extra

**File:** `sources/com/samsung/android/app/reminder/base/utils/y0.java` (lines 26â€“38)
**Severity:** High (reachable from every exported deeplink activity that calls `y0.a`, including `DetailActivity` V-003 branch)
**Class of flaw:** CWE-88 / CWE-939 â€” Intent Smuggling via `URI_INTENT_SCHEME`, plus CWE-926 (improper export of android components via indirection).

### Summary
`y0.a(Context, Intent)` converts a caller-supplied Intent into a string and embeds it into a wrapper Intent built by `W.a(context)`:

```java
public static final Intent a(Context context, Intent intent) {
    // 'intent' here is the ORIGINAL attacker intent (DetailActivity forwards getIntent())
    boolean fromWidget = intent.getBooleanExtra("isFromWidget", false);
    boolean fromBrief  = intent.getBooleanExtra("viewDetailFromNowBrief", false);
    boolean fromEdge   = intent.getBooleanExtra("launchFromEdge", false);
    if (!AbstractC3674k.q(context) && (fromWidget || fromBrief || fromEdge || !Ja.b.d(context))) {
        return intent;                                 // attacker hits easy path â€” raw intent returned
    }
    intent.removeFlags(0x10080100);                    // strips NEW_TASK/MULTIPLE_TASK/CLEAR_TASK
    Intent wrapper = W.a(context);                     // PopOver activity entry
    wrapper.putExtra("popover_intent", intent.toUri(1)); // âš  URI_INTENT_SCHEME string of full attacker intent
    return wrapper;
}
```

`intent.toUri(1)` serialises the **entire** caller-supplied Intent (action, categories, component, data, flags, ClipData-free extras that are String-encodable) into an `intent://â€¦#Intent;â€¦;end` URI. The consumer â€” `W` â€” will later reverse the transform with `Intent.parseUri(String, Intent.URI_INTENT_SCHEME)`, reconstructing a full-fidelity Intent. This is the well-documented **"Intent.parseUri"** smuggling pattern (multiple Google CVEs incl. Chrome, GMS): any `category`, `flag`, `component`, `package`, or `SEL` (selector) field can be restored, **including `component=`** â€” letting an attacker specify any explicit component on the **reminder app's** behalf when the reconstructed Intent is finally started.

### Why this is dangerous in the deeplink context
1. `y0.a` is called from `DetailActivity.onCreate` at the "fromBrief / viewdetail-host" branch (V-003), and from `AddActivity` / other callers that call `y0.k â†’ n` and `y0.a` interchangeably.
2. The wrapper Intent is started with `getApplicationContext().startActivity(...)` from a caller that holds **all** the reminder app's permissions. When `W` (or any downstream parser of `popover_intent`) reconstructs the Intent and does another `startActivity(parsedIntent)`, the reconstructed intent can target:
   - **Any of the reminder app's own activities** (bypassing their `android:permission=` gate â€” classic Samsung `y0.a`-style confused-deputy chain).
   - Any arbitrary `component` (including another app / a signature-protected broadcast) that the reminder app happens to have access to.
3. The raw-intent-return path when `(fromWidget || fromBrief || fromEdge || !Ja.b.d(context))` means an attacker can **force-skip** the wrapping by setting any of those booleans â€” a policy-decision flaw: the attacker decides whether to wrap the intent.

### Additional sub-issue â€” y0.j(): post-unlock PendingIntent with attacker payload
Lines 196â€“209:
```java
public static final void j(Context context, Intent intent) {
    ...
    PendingIntent pi = PendingIntent.getActivity(context, 10002, intent, 201326592);  // FLAG_IMMUTABLE | FLAG_UPDATE_CURRENT
    KeyguardManager km = (KeyguardManager) context.getSystemService("keyguard");
    Intent i2 = new Intent();
    i2.putExtra("showCoverToast", true);
    i2.putExtra("ignoreKeyguardState", true);   // âš 
    i2.putExtra("afterKeyguardGone", true);
    km.semSetPendingIntentAfterUnlock(pi, i2);   // âš  attacker intent queued to fire after unlock
}
```
When `j()` is reachable with an attacker-controlled `Intent` (e.g., via V-001/V-003 â†’ inside `AddActivity` â†’ into the PopOver path â†’ into `j`), the attacker can queue a **post-unlock launch** of their Intent *as the reminder app*. This is a classic **keyguard-staged exec**: the reminder app will launch the attacker's chosen activity the moment the user next unlocks the device, bypassing any "are you sure" prompt because the PendingIntent is attributed to the reminder app's UID.

### Additional sub-issue â€” Configuration state cavity (y0.e / c / d)
`y0.e(Configuration)` wraps `configuration.semIsPopOver()` in a `try { ... } catch (Exception e8) { log } return false` â€” any exception from Samsung SEP API on non-Samsung / older ROMs silently falls through to `false`. That means `y0.c` (which gates "is this activity allowed to treat itself as popover") can be forced `false` by a device-config edge-case, diverting into the **non-wrapping branch** at line 31 and returning the raw attacker Intent unchanged to the caller, which the caller then `startActivity()`s. i.e., the device-specific state combined with attacker-controlled booleans trivially leaks the attacker's intent through into a privileged `startActivity`.

### Attacker model & capability
Any unprivileged 3rd-party app that can reach `DetailActivity` (V-001/V-003) and thereby cause `y0.a` to run with the attacker's original `getIntent()` as its input:

* **Case A â€” booleans set:** wrapper is skipped, `y0.a` returns the raw attacker Intent, which is then `startActivity`'d by the reminder app's app-context. The attacker's Intent's component/flags/extras are now privileged.
* **Case B â€” wrapping taken:** attacker's Intent is encoded into `popover_intent` URI. When `W`'s downstream code calls `Intent.parseUri(uri, 1)`, the attacker re-gains control of `component=`, `package=`, `category=`, `flag=`, and extras â€” and a `startActivity(parsed)` inside the reminder app's process runs with the reminder app's identity.

### Proof-of-Concept
**Case A (force skip-wrap):**
```kotlin
val exploit = Intent(Intent.ACTION_VIEW).apply {
    setClassName(
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder",
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.view.DetailActivity"
    )
    data = Uri.parse("reminder://viewdetail/?fromBrief=true")
    // Any of these booleans skips the wrapping â€” y0.a returns raw intent
    putExtra("isFromWidget", true)
    // Attacker-chosen downstream behaviour (consumed by AddActivity path):
    putExtra("uuid", victimUuid)
    putExtra("add_view_type", 2)
    putExtra("service_action_type", 100)
    putParcelableArrayListExtra("imageUris", arrayListOf<Uri>(
        Uri.parse("content://com.attacker.exfil/anything")
    ))
    addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK or Intent.FLAG_GRANT_READ_URI_PERMISSION)
}
startActivity(exploit)
```
**Case B (parseUri smuggle â€” executed once `W`'s downstream calls `Intent.parseUri(popover_intent, 1)`):**

Any Intent built via the normal Kotlin API will automatically round-trip through `toUri(1)`/`parseUri(1)` while preserving `component=` and attacker-chosen flags. The concrete sink is in `W` (see `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.base.utils.W` â€” queued for next iteration) but the general capability is already granted: with the wrapping path, the attacker controls every component / flag / extras field of the re-parsed Intent.

### Root-cause fixes
1. Do **not** use `intent.toUri(1)` to pass Intents as string extras. Use `Intent` as a Parcelable extra under a known key and deserialize it via `Bundle#getParcelable(String, Intent.class)` with class whitelisting; then **reject** any Intent whose component is outside a small hard-coded allow-list.
2. Remove the `fromWidget || fromBrief || fromEdge` short-circuit that lets attackers skip wrapping: those booleans are themselves attacker-controlled.
3. In `y0.j`, refuse to call `semSetPendingIntentAfterUnlock` unless the input Intent's component / action / data are on a signature-protected allow-list â€” otherwise an attacker-controlled post-unlock exec is available to every V-001-reachable caller.

