## [V-008] `list.main.M.c` â€” `Intent.parseUri(1)` Package-Null Bypass (The Concrete Sink for V-007)

**Files:**
- Sink: `sources/com/samsung/android/app/reminder/ui/list/main/M.java` (lines 33â€“47)
- Wrapper producer: `sources/com/samsung/android/app/reminder/base/utils/W.java` (entire, 24 lines)
- Direct caller: `sources/com/samsung/android/app/reminder/ui/detail/add/D.java` (lines 577â€“578)

**Severity:** High â€” confirms V-007 is exploitable end-to-end.
**Class of flaw:** CWE-436 (interpretation conflict) + CWE-20 + CWE-116 (improper encoding/escaping of output for intent reconstruction).

### Summary â€” sink code
```java
public static final Intent c(String delegateAction) {
    Intent uri;
    try {
        uri = Intent.parseUri(delegateAction, 1);          // URI_INTENT_SCHEME â†’ full Intent
    } catch (URISyntaxException e8) {
        AbstractC0260h.b("MainListActionUtils", "cannotParse " + delegateAction + " " + e8);
        uri = null;
    }
    // âš  only getPackage() is checked; getComponent() is NOT checked
    if ((uri != null ? uri.getPackage() : null) == null
        || "com.samsung.android.app.reminder".equals(uri.getPackage())) {
        return uri;                                        // attacker-controlled Intent returned
    }
    AbstractC0260h.b("MainListActionUtils", "package is not for Reminder");
    return null;
}
```

The guard admits the reconstructed Intent when `uri.getPackage() == null`. An attacker simply omits the `package=` field from the URI string (trivial â€” `Intent.toUri(1)` on an Intent without `setPackage` does not emit a `package=` fragment). Consequently:

* `ComponentName` is **not** validated: the caller can hand back an Intent whose `getComponent()` points to **any** activity â€” including reminder-app activities guarded by `android:permission` (e.g. `AddActivity` itself, `PreReminderActivity`, `CustomPresetActivity`) **or any other installed app's activity**.
* `action`, `categories`, `data`, `flags`, and extras are all preserved from the attacker URI.
* `SEL` (selector intent) is also preserved â€” a second-stage redirect vector.

### Wrapper producer (already done by V-007 path)
`y0.a(Context, Intent)` calls `W.a(context).putExtra("popover_intent", intent.toUri(1))`. `W.a` itself is a tiny factory:
```java
public abstract class W {
    public static final Uri f28389a = Uri.parse("content://com.sec.android.app.launcher.settings");

    public static Intent a(Context context) {
        Intent i = context.getPackageManager().getLaunchIntentForPackage(context.getPackageName());
        if (i == null) {
            i = new Intent();
            i.setAction("com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.ReminderMainListView");
            i.setClassName("com.samsung.android.app.reminder",
                           "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.list.main.MainListActivity");
        }
        i.setPackage(null).addFlags(0x14200000).addCategory("android.intent.category.LAUNCHER").removeCategory("android.intent.category.INFO");
        return i;
    }
}
```
`0x14200000` = `FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK | FLAG_ACTIVITY_LAUNCH_ADJACENT | FLAG_ACTIVITY_RESET_TASK_IF_NEEDED`. `setPackage(null)` makes this wrapper usable as an implicit-enough launch intent. `W` itself only produces the carrier; the sink is downstream.

### End-to-end reachability
`popover_intent` is consumed by multiple callers (`rg popover_intent`):
1. `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.add.D.java:577` â†’ `getStringExtra("popover_intent")` â†’ `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.list.main.M.c(stringExtra2)` (line 578).
2. `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.add.D.java:749` â†’ `Intent.parseUri(str3, 1)` (a second parseUri â€” needs its own analysis, queued).
3. `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.list.main.R1.java:1094` â†’ reads `popover_intent`, then at line 1098 re-puts it on a fresh Intent to `AddActivity` with action `ReminderAddView`.
4. `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.list.main.MainListActivity.java:1727` â€” `hasExtra("popover_intent")` gate.
5. `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.quickadd.G1.java:77` â€” producer side (another `toUri(1)`).

The AddActivity path (1) is directly exploitable via `D.l(intent)` â€” a function already on tracking (`D` â€” [ëŚ€ę¸°]). Once `M.c(stringExtra2)` returns the attacker-smuggled Intent, `D.l` proceeds to act on it (`intentC = â€¦ M.c(â€¦)`), giving the attacker a reminder-app-initiated `startActivity(intentC)` equivalent.

### Attacker capability
Chained with V-001 (DetailActivity bypass) and V-007 (y0.a/j wrapping), an unprivileged 3rd-party app can:

* Launch `AddActivity` with a `popover_intent` URI that explicitly targets **any** permission-protected activity of the reminder app (confused-deputy elevation), or any world-reachable activity of another app.
* Set action = `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.ReminderAddView` on the smuggled Intent â€” obtaining the effect of holding `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.permission.action.REGISTER` without holding it.
* Add `SEL` selector that, after `startActivity`, diverts to a second component.
* Combine with V-007's `y0.j` post-unlock stage â€” the smuggled Intent becomes a PendingIntent that fires after unlock.

### Proof-of-Concept

**1) Direct push of a smuggled Intent URI into AddActivity:**
```kotlin
